  "prompt": "What happens legally if someone is caught laundering money?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious criminal offense with potentially severe legal consequences. Typically, if someone is caught laundering money, they may face:\n\n1. Criminal Charges\n- Federal or state criminal prosecution\n- Potential felony charges\n- Significant prison time (often several years)\n- Large financial penalties/fines\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Seizure of illegally obtained assets\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeitures\n\n3. Additional Legal Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty finding future employment\n- Potential civil lawsuits\n\n4. Prosecution Process\n- Investigation by agencies like FBI or IRS\n- Potential arraignment and trial\n- Possibility of plea bargaining\n\nThe specific consequences depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Sophistication of the laundering scheme\n- Prior criminal history\n- Specific jurisdiction's laws\n\nPenalties can vary significantly based on individual circumstances, but money laundering is treated as a very serious financial crime.",
